00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Look at what you're seeing. Lane departure warnings that annoy customers — you can explain how the system works and how to adjust sensitivity. Touch-free trunk that seems difficult — you can demonstrate the proper technique. Voice recognition that doesn't seem to work — you can show them the right phrasing and timing. Here's the critical insight: studies show that if a customer doesn't successfully use a feature within thirty days of delivery, they abandon it. They declare it a failure. It goes into their IQS response as a problem. But you can prevent that abandonment. Take two or three minutes to explain or demonstrate a feature when you notice a customer struggling. You've just turned a potential IQS complaint into customer satisfaction. You've shown you care about their complete ownership experience, not just fixing their car. Not every issue can be solved with education — some are legitimate defects that need diagnosis and repair. But many can be addressed through your communication and your willingness to help customers understand their vehicles. This is what separates adequate service from exceptional service. It's also what builds the kind of trust that creates loyal, long-term customers.
